<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ880106-0112 </DOCNO><HL> Mott's Super Markets Gets Bid to Go Private </HL><SO> </SO><CO> MSM </CO><IN> TNM </IN><DATELINE> EAST HARTFORD, Conn.  </DATELINE><TEXT>   Mott's Super Markets Inc. said a group of its managers and controlling shareholders offered to take the company private at $11.50 a share in a transaction with an indicated value of $9.3 million.    Barry Baskind, Mott's president, said about 71% of the company's approximately 2.8 million common shares outstanding is owned by the Mott and Baskind families. The families are offering to buy the shares they don't already own, he said.    In American Stock Exchange composite trading yesterday, Mott's shares closed at $9.25, up 25 cents.    The company said that the offer is being evaluated by a committee of outside directors, who are scheduled to meet with an investment banking firm to evaluate its fairness. Mr. Baskind declined to identify the investment banker or to elaborate on the offer. </TEXT></DOC>